revision.text:
{{US}} {{hatnote|For a full discussion, see [https://www.investopedia.com/terms/s/sarsep.asp Salary Reduction Simplified Employee Pension Plan (SARSEP) Definition]}}
A '''Salary Reduction Simplified Employee Pension Plan''' (SARSEP) is a simplified employee pension ([[SEP]]) plan set up before 1997 that includes a salary reduction arrangement. Under a SARSEP, employees can choose to have the employer contribute part of their pay to their Individual Retirement Account or Annuity (IRA) set up under the SARSEP (a SEP-IRA). A SARSEP may not be established after 1996. However, for SARSEPs set up before 1997, eligible employees hired after 1996 must be allowed to participate.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.irs.gov/retirement-plans/plan-sponsor/salary-reduction-simplified-employee-pension-plan-sarsep| title=Salary Reduction Simplified Employee Pension plan (SARSEP)| publisher=IRS| accessdate=July 9, 2025}}</ref>
The Economic Growth and Tax Relief Reconciliation Act of 2001 (EGTRRA) changed many of the Internal Revenue Code's requirements and limits for qualified plans and IRAs. If a model SARSEP plan was used, an updated model plan should have been adopted by the end of 2002 to take advantage of new law changes.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.irs.gov/retirement-plans/retirement-plans-faqs-regarding-sarseps#3| title=Retirement plans FAQs regarding SARSEPs| publisher=IRS| accessdate=July 9, 2025}}</ref>
