{{for|a full discussion|wikipedia:Deferred compensation}}

'''{{PAGENAME}}''' is an arrangement where an employer pays out some part of an employee's income at a date later than they earned the income. Examples include pensions, retirement plans, and stock options. The primary benefit of most deferred compensation plans is that they defer tax.

When used in context as an employer's ''Deferred compensation plan'', it refers to a contract between employer and employee. See: [[Employer retirement plans overview#Deferred compensation plan (non-qualified) | Deferred compensation plan]].

