[[Category:Glossary]]
[[Category:Employer provided retirement plans]]

{{US|reason=irrelevant}}

U.S. regulations permit "in service" tax free transfer of certain accounts, under specific circumstances. These types of transfers may be useful if you hold SIMPLE IRA accounts or deferred variable annuities. Under some circumstances, if you have a 403(b) plan you may also be able to transfer accounts while still working for your employer. To remain tax deferred, these transfers are all trustee-to-trustee exchanges between the companies providing the accounts.

==SIMPLE IRA transfers==
{{main|SIMPLE IRA}}

Although SIMPLE IRAs are a small part of the employer-provided qualified plan universe, they are the only plan that currently let you exchange in-service trustee-to-trustee, to a provider you choose. The first consideration when choosing a SIMPLE-IRA provider is to determine the type of SIMPLE IRA your employer has established, either an [http://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-pdf/f5304sim.pdf IRS Form 5304-SIMPLE] or an [http://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-pdf/f5305sim.pdf IRS Form 5305-SIMPLE].

* '''IRS Form 5304-SIMPLE''': this and similar forms of a SIMPLE IRA let you choose the financial institution for receiving contributions. The employer is required to send contributions on your behalf directly to your chosen financial institution. Most participants are unaware of this option, so you need to check with your employer to see what form was used to create the plan. Obviously, if you have this type of SIMPLE-IRA you can choose a low cost provider, and then invest all your salary deferral and employer match in low cost funds.
* '''IRS Form 5305-SIMPLE''': this and similar forms of SIMPLE IRA require all contributions to be deposited initially at your designated chosen financial institution. You must transfer trustee-to-trustee to invest with your chosen provider. During the first two years of participating in a SIMPLE IRA, you can only transfer to another SIMPLE IRA. After two years (dated from the first contribution into the plan) you can transfer into a Traditional IRA.

With Form 5305-SIMPLE IRAs you should always try to reduce transfer costs by choosing the lowest cost fund in your employer's plan for accumulating assets for transfer. For load fund SIMPLE IRAs this is usually restricted to a no-load share class of a money market fund. Because your on-going salary deferrals and employer matches will be deposited with the employer's provider, avoiding front end loads and back end surrender charges is essential in reducing transfer costs.

==403(b) transfers==
{{main|403(b)}}

Before September 24, 2007, if you held a high-cost 403(b) plans you could take advantage of the 90-24 Transfer provision of the IRS code and transfer plan assets in-service trustee-to-trustee to your chosen outside provider. The finalized IRS 403(b) regulations, operational after January 1, 2009, have terminated the 90-24 provision. However, under the current interpretation of the new regulations,<ref> [http://m.403bwise.com/wisemoves/newtransferrules.html New transfer rules],{{broken link}} 403(b)wise.com.</ref> in-service trustee-to-trustee transfers may still be possible if certain conditions are met. 403(b) investors can move to low-cost providers in two ways under the new regulations:

* The employer may select a low cost provider as an option within the plan;
* The employer may permit exchanges and establish a formal information sharing relationship with an outside low cost provider.<ref group="note">The IRS allows 403(b) contract exchanges with a non-payroll slot vendor if:
*the plan permits the exchange;
*the accumulated benefit after the exchange is at least the same as before the exchange;
*the employer and the non-payroll slot vendor agree to share information regarding employment and the plan’s terms;
*any pre-exchange benefit restrictions are maintained after the exchange; and
*the vendor complies with the plan’s terms.  See [https://www.irs.gov/retirement-plans/retirement-plans-faqs-regarding-403b-tax-sheltered-annuity-plans#15 What are the rules on in-service transfers or exchanges], IRS FAQs regarding 403(b) Tax Sheltered Annuity Plans.</ref> 

If Vanguard's information sharing document is not accepted by the employer, it is possible that the documents from [[Fidelity]], [[T. Rowe Price]], or [[TIAA-CREF]] may be accepted, so that you can transfer to a 403(b)(7)<ref group="note"> A 403(b)(7) designation refers to a 403(b) plan that is funded by investments in mutual funds.</ref> portfolio available from these providers.

If you are thinking of doing this, try to minimize your transfer costs by choosing an employer plan investment option that is exempt from front or back end loads, or stiff annuity surrender fees. Many current 403(b) investors will be subject to these surrender fees; something to consider when assessing the feasibility of an exchange.

==1035 exchanges of non-qualifying variable annuities==
{{main|Variable Annuity}}

Because variable annuities typically have high insurance costs and stiff back end surrender fees, a tax-free exchange of high cost contracts to a no-load, no surrender fee, low cost variable annuity is clearly useful for most non-qualifying annuities. This type of transfer is known as a 1035 transfer<ref group="note"> See [http://www.investopedia.com/terms/s/sec1035ex.asp 1035 transfer], Investopedia. The 1035 exchange also applies to transfers of fixed deferred annuities and cash value life insurance contracts.</ref> The annuity option variables to include in a calculation are:<ref>{{cite web| url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=496025| title=Exchanging Variable Annuities: An Optional Test for Suitability| author1=Moshe A. Milevsky| author2=Kamphol Panyagometh| date=2004| accessdate=June 27, 2025}} Available from SSRN.</ref>

* '''Lapse value'''. This captures the cash-flow that comes from liquidating or surrendering the policy – possibly after paying a contingent deferred surrender charge (CDSC) – and is tied to the evolution of the market value of the sub-accounts. Most investors purchase VAs exclusively for their lapse value since they view the instrument as a (tax-preferred) savings vehicle. Therefore, when contemplating an exchange, be aware of the discounted lapse value (DLV) of the new policy. All else being equal, the greater the contingent deferred surrender charges (CDSC) on the new policy and/or the greater the Mortality and Expense Risk Fees (from here, abbreviated M&E Fee) relative to the old policy, the lower the discounted lapse value, and the less likely it is that an exchange will be beneficial.
* '''Death value'''. Most VA policies contain some form of guaranteed minimum death benefit. This guarantee comes in various shapes and flavors, but usually consists of a return-of-premium guarantee together with a minimally guaranteed interest rate and/or anniversary step-up feature, which periodically raises the minimum guarantee to market value. And, while these guaranteed minimum death benefits (GMDB) (as they are collectively known) have become a recent nuisance to the risk management and treasury departments within the insurance companies issuing these policies, most consumers are more likely to lapse their VA than die and cash-in on the GMDB. Nevertheless, this embedded option must be priced in any transaction; the term discounted mortality value (DMV) denotes the current value of this guarantee.
* '''Guaranteed Annuity Rates'''. All variable annuity policies contain an option to annuitize – in the form of a guaranteed mortality table and interest rate – which is poorly understood and usually ignored. Many older VAs contain annuity rate guarantees that are linked to outdated mortality tables and so are more valuable, relative to updated mortality tables that assume a longer life expectancy. More recent VA policies offer optional guaranteed minimum income benefit (GMIB) riders which are a form of guaranteed annuity rate. In general, the term discounted annuity value (DAV) denotes the collection of options associated with the ability to annuitize the policy at a pre-specified mortality table and interest rate.

