{{Retirement accounts}}
{{TSP}}
[[Category:Employer provided retirement plans]]
[[Category:Thrift Savings Plan]]
[[Category:Pages requiring annual tax updates]]

{{US|reason=irrelevant}}
The so-called '''Rule of 55''' allows you to withdraw from a [[401(k)]] or [[403(b)]] without paying the 10% early withdrawal penalty on withdrawals you make after separating from service, if you separate from the sponsoring employer in or after the calendar year you turn 55. The rule does not apply to [[IRA|IRAs]]. This rule can allow you to access retirement money without penalty up to 5½ years earlier (if your birthday is late in the year and you separate early in the year you turn 55) than waiting until age 59½, the normal age where early withdrawal penalties get waived.
There are other ways to [[User:Fyre4ce/Early withdrawal|withdraw early]] from a retirement account without penalty.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.irs.gov/retirement-plans/plan-participant-employee/retirement-topics-exceptions-to-tax-on-early-distributions| title=Retirement topics - Exceptions to tax on early distributions| publisher=IRS| accessdate=August 25, 2025}}</ref> The decision of whether to [[Early retirement|retire early]] can be an impactful one, so make sure you have planned appropriately.
The term "Rule of 55" is not an official government term, although it is used ubiquitously throughout the finance community. The IRS uses the official term "Separation from service" to describe this exception to the early withdrawal penalty. The rules are laid out in Internal Revenue Code sections 72(t)(2)(A)(v) and 72(t)(10).
==Constraints==
*The Rule of 55 (hereafter, "the rule") only applies to [[401(k)]], [[403(b)]], and [[457(b)]] accounts, and the [[Thrift Savings Plan]]. It does not apply to [[IRA|IRAs]], even if you first [[IRA rollovers and transfers|roll money out]] of one of these accounts into an IRA. It also does not apply if you resume working for a new employer and roll the money into the new plan, unless you separate from the new employer before you turn 59½. *The rule applies only if you separate anytime within the year you turn 55, or after,<ref group="note">This is in contrast normal early withdrawal penalties, which apply down to the day - that is, you will owe a 10% penalty if you withdraw even one day before you turn 59½. The IRS defines age 59½ as six months after your 59th birthday.</ref> and only applies to withdrawals taken after your separation date. If you separate before the calendar year you turn 55, you cannot later take advantage of the rule when you turn 55. *The rule applies only to the plan at an employer you separate from in or after the year you turn 55. The rule does not apply to plans at former employers. However, you may be able to roll money at a former employer into the current employer's plan, making it eligible for the rule. *Plans are not required to allow you to make partial withdrawals after you separate, in which case the rule is nearly useless.<ref group="note">There may be more complex ways to work around this restriction. For example, you could perform an indirect rollover to an IRA, and retain the amount you need until you turn 59½ from the rollover. This strategy would have a more benign tax impact if you are closer to 59½ than 55, and if you have other sources of money to help fund this period.</ref> You would have to take lump sum withdrawal, which would concentrate a large amount of taxable income in a single year, and forego future tax-protected growth.
==Other details==
*The reason for terminating employment (e.g., quitting, retiring, laid off, fired) is not relevant, but the employment relationship must be completely severed.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-wd/00-0245.pdf| title=Sarbanes letter| publisher=IRS| accessdate=September 3, 2025}}</ref> Merely switching to part-time does not count, nor would separating and then rehiring just for the purpose of activating the rule. The rule would apply if you are rehired after some period of time, as long as there was a legitimate change in circumstances, but the plan might not allow you to withdraw in this case, making the rule useless. The rule also applies if you convert to independent contractor status. *You can terminate employment more than once. For example, if you leave employer A in the year you turn 55, and start working for employer B when you are 57, you can still take penalty-free withdrawals from the plan at employer A. If you leave employer B before you turn 59½, you can take penalty-free withdrawals from ''both'' plans. *For some public safety employees, such as police officers, firefighters, EMTs, and air traffic controllers, the rule applies in the calendar year in which they turn '''50''', or with 25 years of service under the plan, whichever comes first.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.schwab.com/learn/story/retiring-early-5-key-points-about-rule-55| title=When Can You Withdraw? 401(k)s and the Rule of 55| publisher=Charles Schwab| author=Hayden Adams| date=April 1, 2025| accessdate=August 25, 2025}}</ref> *457(b) plans normally do not have any early withdrawal penalties. However, governmental 457(b) plans can accept rollovers from other types of accounts, and any non-457(b) money withdrawn before age 59½ has an early withdrawal penalty unless an exception applies. The rule waives penalties on any non-457 withdrawals. *Even though the rule waives the 10% early withdrawal penalty, you will still owe income taxes on withdrawals you make from pre-tax (also known as "traditional") accounts. *The rule also applies to withdrawals from a designated Roth account (for example, [[401(k)#Roth_401(k)|Roth 401(k)]]). But, while the rule will waive penalties on withdrawals, the earnings that have accrued inside the account are still taxable until the Roth account is ''qualified.'' The account becomes qualified when you have met the 5-year period of participation since your first contribution to this account, ''and'' you are either 59½ or disabled. For non-qualified withdrawals, earnings and basis are pro-rata.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.irs.gov/retirement-plans/retirement-plans-faqs-on-designated-roth-accounts| title=Retirement plans FAQs on designated Roth accounts| publisher=IRS| accessdate=August 25, 2025}}</ref> For this reason, a rollover to Roth IRA is suggested where the withdrawal rules do not require the earnings and basis to be pro-rated.
